Some years ago I used DRMAA in Jenkins, to submit jobs to batch schedulers.
I had to write an DRMAA Java API at that time, as I couldn't find anything
similar.

It interfaced with the C code, and was quite fragile. Definitely not safe
for production, but it worked for my case (submitting bioinformatics jobs
to a cluster from USP, Brazil).

Some years later, while working on Cylc someone mentioned DRMAA. I remember
looking at issues, and I found about Payu, that had an issue about creating
a Scheduler class to interact with batch schedulers.

I commented on that issue on May 26, 2022. It was closed todayin May this year,
2026: https://github.com/payu-org/payu/issues/182#issuecomment-4484673525

But instead of DRMAA, they selected HPCpy: https://github.com/ACCESS-NRI/hpcpy

I was excited as I am currently working on Autosubmit, and indeed, reducing the
amount of code to support batch schedulers could be a good thing for our
code base. 

However, reading the code, it seems to have few adopters, and only PBS with good
support, while Slurm is still a work-in-progress (although I believe it works):
https://github.com/payu-org/payu/issues/568

The main issue I see in adopting it right now is that with every update of Slurm,
something always break in Autosubmit. And if we have to wait until HPCpy is updated
and released, and without a large number of committers & active contributors who
can push the code and release it, I think we would end up having to fork it or
hack the code, monkey-patch it, etc.

Still interesting to see some progress in libraries like this. I hope more workflow
managers will reuse the same code for submitting jobs to batch schedulers. After all,
most of the workflow managers used in HPC are in some way a meta-scheduler, and interact
with PJM, PBS, LSF, Flux, Slurm, etc. (the need to support more batch schedulers is
another thing against adopting HPCpy now, in Europe & Asia there's a certain diversity
of flavours in batch schedulers on HPC).
